1
00:00:00,622 --> 00:00:30,510
Namo tassa bhagavato arhato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arhato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arhato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

2
00:00:33,375 --> 00:00:37,726
I just thought I'd continue that theme of relationship.

3
00:00:39,991 --> 00:00:48,533
Normally at Christmas I do the paramis, the ten perfections.

4
00:00:50,857 --> 00:00:54,582
The perfections were, it translates to the word parama, which means the other shore.

5
00:00:54,963 --> 00:00:56,585
It's what takes you to the other shore.

6
00:00:57,485 --> 00:01:04,615
They were a later collection of what the commentaries thought was important about the Buddha's teachings.

7
00:01:07,239 --> 00:01:14,548
But just to try and put it in, I'll just speak them and then you can see what they are.

8
00:01:15,168 --> 00:01:18,233
So there's dana, there's giving, there's morality.

9
00:01:19,832 --> 00:01:20,814
There's renunciation.

10
00:01:21,695 --> 00:01:24,921
There's wisdom, which is a mental virtue.

11
00:01:25,721 --> 00:01:34,775
Energy, patience, truthfulness, resolution, loving-kindness, and equanimity.

12
00:01:35,656 --> 00:01:41,046
So those are the ten that were chosen by the wise ones out of the Buddhist teachings.

13
00:01:41,066 --> 00:01:46,414
And as you know, the Mahayana only have six, so that makes us much more superior.

14
00:01:49,144 --> 00:01:53,090
Just to talk about relationships.

15
00:01:53,109 --> 00:02:07,167
So, remember that we were sort of trying to say last night that there's a part of the Buddha's teachings about insights, about actually understanding who and what we are and all that sort of stuff and how we create suffering.

16
00:02:07,828 --> 00:02:12,873
But the other part is how it expresses itself in the world through our relationships.

17
00:02:13,816 --> 00:02:20,913
Occasionally when I watch these videos on TED, have you come across TED?

18
00:02:22,358 --> 00:02:26,649
It's a website that has lots of talks by experts and stuff.

19
00:02:26,748 --> 00:02:28,212
Some are very, very, well, I like them.

20
00:02:29,188 --> 00:02:36,638
But these people who are into positive psychology, you know, they come across this word, you come across this word connections.

21
00:02:37,239 --> 00:02:46,810
That's their way of expressing relationship, which to me is really just about reducing it to some sort of communication in a way.

22
00:02:47,311 --> 00:02:53,138
Because academics will always try to find another word on the presumption that they're coming up with something remarkably new.

23
00:02:54,838 --> 00:02:58,123
It's quite difficult to use ordinary words like relationship.

24
00:02:59,205 --> 00:03:07,116
So the fundamental relationship that the Buddhas talk about, and which is throughout the East, of course, is ahimsa, no harm.

25
00:03:08,078 --> 00:03:10,461
And this was variously translated.

26
00:03:10,580 --> 00:03:17,631
So the Jains, as you know, thought that when you did harm, even if you didn't mean it, you were going to get your comeuppance.

27
00:03:18,271 --> 00:03:22,197
So he basically avoided stepping on ants and all that sort of stuff.

28
00:03:22,397 --> 00:03:23,479
They'd come back and

29
00:03:23,459 --> 00:03:24,841
bite you in the bum or something.

30
00:03:26,163 --> 00:03:46,495
And you see them, you know, brushing their way before they take a step as a sort of a very, I think it's a very great sensitivity to the amount of harm we can do just because either we're not aware of it or we don't want to be aware of it and so on.

31
00:03:46,534 --> 00:03:48,116
It's just ignorance, is it?

32
00:03:49,531 --> 00:03:53,156
But from the Buddha's point of view, that wasn't really the problem.

33
00:03:54,336 --> 00:04:00,025
His problem was always to do with how we create suffering for ourselves.

34
00:04:00,544 --> 00:04:02,106
And therefore it was an internal thing.

35
00:04:03,368 --> 00:04:10,998
And he brought it down to this whole business of intention, empowering an intention.

36
00:04:10,979 --> 00:04:14,282
So when we empower intention, remember, you create a habit.

37
00:04:15,743 --> 00:04:19,107
An action, you know, the usual progression.

38
00:04:19,827 --> 00:04:26,413
An intention, an action, a habit, a personality, and a destiny.

39
00:04:27,355 --> 00:04:28,536
That's the sort of trajectory.

40
00:04:29,216 --> 00:04:31,978
So our personalities are just these combination of habits.

41
00:04:33,341 --> 00:04:37,644
And it's really recognizing what a habit's doing, if it's doing any harm,

42
00:04:37,961 --> 00:04:44,293
then to undermine it, to not go with those particular intentions.

43
00:04:45,636 --> 00:04:52,848
But our inner intentional life, of course, expresses itself outwardly.

44
00:04:53,064 --> 00:04:58,130
in obvious ways in what we do, in more subtle ways in body language.

45
00:04:58,891 --> 00:05:03,737
And this immediately creates a connection, to use that wonderful word.

46
00:05:03,757 --> 00:05:06,180
So you're establishing a relationship.

47
00:05:06,961 --> 00:05:18,194
And the relationships are telling us what we're giving out in the world, even when we're not actually fully aware of it.

48
00:05:19,254 --> 00:05:32,735
You know, people with, well, and obviously with passive aggression, you know, where the person's obviously manifesting aggression, but when you say they're angry, they say, not me, I never get angry.

49
00:05:33,538 --> 00:05:41,189
And it's that sort of inability to see ourselves as we are, even in relationship.

50
00:05:41,589 --> 00:05:45,836
But when something happens in a relationship, it's mirroring something back to us.

51
00:05:46,254 --> 00:05:49,899
Of course, you've always got to take into consideration that the other person's doing the same.

52
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:55,185
So that's another thing we say, isn't it, that when two people meet, there are six people there.

53
00:05:55,706 --> 00:05:59,992
There's me as I see myself, there's me as you see me, and there's me as I really am.

54
00:06:00,413 --> 00:06:01,374
And the same applies to you.

55
00:06:01,894 --> 00:06:11,266
So in this sort of web of delusion, it's very difficult to work out how or why things go wrong.

56
00:06:11,720 --> 00:06:30,918
But in terms of the Buddha's teachings, at the root of this problem lies this acquisitiveness, this desire, and deeper than that, this sort of sense of thirst, of lack.

57
00:06:30,939 --> 00:06:32,581
Other writers use that word, lack.

58
00:06:35,863 --> 00:06:39,668
And in order to undermine that,

59
00:06:41,403 --> 00:06:49,810
We practice certain things that cut deep into that business of finding safety, finding happiness in acquisition.

60
00:06:51,035 --> 00:06:53,944
And that's the process of renunciation.

61
00:06:55,408 --> 00:07:00,857
So again, I'm sure you all know the distinction that's often made between renunciation and mortification.

62
00:07:00,937 --> 00:07:09,088
So mortification was based on some idea that the soul was held down by the heaviness of the body.

63
00:07:09,810 --> 00:07:16,218
You get it in Christian understanding too, don't you?

64
00:07:16,199 --> 00:07:20,185
You know, if the eye offends you, pluck it out.

65
00:07:20,206 --> 00:07:22,069
So people often believe it's the body at fault.

66
00:07:22,932 --> 00:07:23,992
Sex is at fault.

67
00:07:24,694 --> 00:07:28,382
Our sexual powers are what's evil, not the way we use them.

68
00:07:28,541 --> 00:07:32,389
That's the devil drawing us down, you see, into the pleasures of life.

69
00:07:33,831 --> 00:07:35,574
So...

70
00:07:36,802 --> 00:07:46,122
The idea was, well, one idea was at that time, of course, that as you undermined the pleasures of the body, the soul released itself.

71
00:07:46,142 --> 00:07:50,432
And you often get that sort of self-mortification in other religions too.

72
00:07:51,494 --> 00:07:53,158
The Buddha saw that as just more suffering.

73
00:07:54,555 --> 00:07:57,259
But he didn't give up the idea of renunciation, you see.

74
00:07:57,781 --> 00:08:03,050
It shifted, the definition shifted, and it shifted to giving something up to see where the attachment was.

75
00:08:03,189 --> 00:08:03,891
It's as simple as that.

76
00:08:03,911 --> 00:08:15,449
So our fast, you know, depending on what came up for you in the fast, would show you at times your attachment to certain patterns of behavior, you see.

77
00:08:17,692 --> 00:08:22,098
Now that would be a sort of negative use of renunciation.

78
00:08:22,317 --> 00:08:26,783
In other words, you're positively giving something up in order to see where your attachment is.

79
00:08:28,565 --> 00:08:43,446
So, for instance, we might disguise our loneliness, everybody feels lonely at some time or other, by distracting ourselves, you know, watching TV, listening to radio, always having some input, you see, so we're never actually in contact with the inner person.

80
00:08:44,674 --> 00:08:52,450
And then when you go into a silence and there's nothing there and you're not distracting the mind, then suddenly you're on your own, you see.

81
00:08:52,910 --> 00:08:59,123
And in that oneness, there's a sort of feeling of being abandoned, unloved.

82
00:08:59,659 --> 00:09:00,341
Nobody loves me.

83
00:09:00,360 --> 00:09:00,841
How could they?

84
00:09:00,922 --> 00:09:01,282
I'm horrible.

85
00:09:02,484 --> 00:09:09,653
And it's getting in touch with that nasty feeling of loneliness and unlovedness and all that sort of stuff.

86
00:09:10,214 --> 00:09:19,947
But, of course, we would do it in order to get in touch with it, to feel it, to actually begin to explore that feeling and find out where its basis was, where it's coming from.

87
00:09:20,956 --> 00:09:34,312
And we also know that in that exploration, that malevolent energy that we've created through attachment, you see, we have defined love as how much another person can fulfill our needs.

88
00:09:35,113 --> 00:09:37,456
That's what we understand the love to be.

89
00:09:37,897 --> 00:09:40,840
So when there's nobody there to fulfill our needs, then of course I'm completely unloved.

90
00:09:41,400 --> 00:09:43,182
I mean, no Christmas present.

91
00:09:43,163 --> 00:09:46,886
I don't get any more Christmas presents.

92
00:09:47,508 --> 00:09:55,697
So when we cut deep into that, and we just, when we say cut deep into it, we're not trying to understand it intellectually.

93
00:09:56,136 --> 00:09:57,719
See, then that takes you off somewhere else.

94
00:09:58,100 --> 00:10:02,203
Cutting deep means going right into the pain of loneliness.

95
00:10:02,524 --> 00:10:03,785
You know, take that as an example.

96
00:10:04,225 --> 00:10:05,727
Then, of course, we find that

97
00:10:05,707 --> 00:10:07,293
you know, it begins to transform.

98
00:10:07,312 --> 00:10:10,000
The transformation happens quite naturally.

99
00:10:10,020 --> 00:10:11,365
It can happen very suddenly.

100
00:10:11,405 --> 00:10:18,267
Suddenly you find it's gone and you're perfectly happy with yourself and you've discovered solitude, you know.

101
00:10:21,014 --> 00:10:26,964
Other times it sort of fades out, but there's a sort of a murky sort of stuff there and not going anywhere.

102
00:10:27,384 --> 00:10:33,455
But even so, some of that energy is in the process of transforming, of moving to the upper.

103
00:10:33,514 --> 00:10:36,340
In fact, I'm trying to use this new word, sublimating.

104
00:10:38,243 --> 00:10:41,688
It just, there's no in-between state, it goes from one state to the other.

105
00:10:47,423 --> 00:10:55,464
So that's the negative, to use that word, use of renunciation.

106
00:10:55,825 --> 00:11:00,538
We're trying to find out where we're stuck, where we're holding on to things, trying to let go of things, you see.

107
00:11:00,990 --> 00:11:07,101
But any time we behave from the heart of love, there must be some form of renunciation.

108
00:11:07,621 --> 00:11:09,865
And the Buddha points this out in dana.

109
00:11:11,129 --> 00:11:14,333
That's one of his main teachings, dana, which is generosity.

110
00:11:14,995 --> 00:11:17,480
Whenever he's talking to lay people, he always starts with dana.

111
00:11:17,620 --> 00:11:20,283
And he points out that anybody can be generous, even a thief.

112
00:11:20,465 --> 00:11:24,291
You know, like after they've stolen your money, they can give it to somebody else who's in need.

113
00:11:24,792 --> 00:11:25,833
Or Robin Hood, you know.

114
00:11:26,658 --> 00:11:39,659
So, for generosity, it comes even before sila, which means these five basic rules of no harm that we chant every morning.

115
00:11:40,361 --> 00:11:41,322
It's even before that.

116
00:11:41,403 --> 00:11:50,538
You can be a really, you know, ugly, terrible person, but still be kind to your dog and give it biscuits when it's hungry.

117
00:11:50,519 --> 00:11:55,465
So that's the easiest one to generate.

118
00:11:55,885 --> 00:12:00,051
Now, of course, every time you're generous, you must be giving something up for the benefit of somebody else.

119
00:12:01,293 --> 00:12:16,071
So just in that process, there is a process of renunciation, and renunciation here, you know, not feeding into myself, into my selfish needs, and giving it up for somebody else.

120
00:12:18,008 --> 00:12:25,067
And so one of the things, of course, that excites, and this is the little matrix that sort of spins around, are these three things.

121
00:12:25,488 --> 00:12:33,789
What makes generosity very easy, at least to practice, is developing gratitude.

122
00:12:34,697 --> 00:12:42,292
I remember once reading Meister Eckhart, 13th century mystic, who said that if the whole of your life you said thank you, that would be enough.

123
00:12:42,631 --> 00:12:43,815
I mean, that was his.

124
00:12:45,157 --> 00:12:50,447
That's how important he felt this attitude of gratitude was, you know.

125
00:12:50,466 --> 00:12:51,128
Thankfulness.

126
00:12:52,149 --> 00:12:57,820
I think it's one of the nice things of America that they have that Thanksgiving Day.

127
00:12:57,799 --> 00:13:00,604
I think we have one, don't we?

128
00:13:02,927 --> 00:13:07,673
Doesn't the Church of England have an autumn Thanksgiving, doesn't it?

129
00:13:07,693 --> 00:13:08,195
Is that what it is?

130
00:13:09,096 --> 00:13:11,078
No.

131
00:13:11,099 --> 00:13:14,083
When they collect all the stuff for harvest.

132
00:13:15,225 --> 00:13:16,167
Harvest festival, isn't it?

133
00:13:16,187 --> 00:13:16,727
Is that what you said?

134
00:13:17,388 --> 00:13:17,788
Harvest?

135
00:13:18,169 --> 00:13:19,572
Oh, sorry, I thought you said hog.

136
00:13:20,874 --> 00:13:21,554
Don't ask me why.

137
00:13:24,739 --> 00:13:26,000
You said harvest, I heard hog.

138
00:13:28,798 --> 00:13:29,879
You see how wars start.

139
00:13:32,602 --> 00:13:37,687
In fact, it reminds me of a lovely moment in the car with my family when I was driving her somewhere.

140
00:13:38,448 --> 00:13:42,452
And my mother was in a bit of a little depressed, angry little mood.

141
00:13:42,472 --> 00:13:43,573
And she was sat at the back glum.

142
00:13:44,835 --> 00:13:46,376
My father was saying something.

143
00:13:46,397 --> 00:13:48,239
He was a bit high and being jolly.

144
00:13:48,739 --> 00:13:50,780
And he said, oh, come on, Rosa, cheer up.

145
00:13:50,900 --> 00:13:53,024
And she said, oh, well, you shut up.

146
00:13:53,043 --> 00:13:56,346
That was brilliant.

147
00:13:56,807 --> 00:13:57,388
So...

148
00:14:01,250 --> 00:14:13,929
So this little virtuous circle of gratitude, when you think about just what we've received from society.

149
00:14:15,172 --> 00:14:25,707
I remember somebody grumbling to me once that they didn't have any children, she didn't have any children, and she didn't know why she paid taxes so that other children could be educated.

150
00:14:26,288 --> 00:14:28,152
She found that absolutely obnoxious.

151
00:14:29,465 --> 00:14:38,802
So when you begin to realize that actually a lot of our education has been, you know, given to us by the generous taxation of other people.

152
00:14:39,604 --> 00:14:47,099
And it's just things like that and things that we take for granted that, you know, because of our social system.

153
00:14:47,679 --> 00:14:48,942
You know...

154
00:14:48,922 --> 00:15:01,154
doctors, the NHS, I mean, there's all sorts of things which we presume now, you know, we don't see them as something which is gifted to us.

155
00:15:01,174 --> 00:15:04,418
Not that we don't pay our taxes, but...

156
00:15:04,438 --> 00:15:10,706
So, gratitude enlivens this idea of generosity.

157
00:15:12,287 --> 00:15:12,988
And...

158
00:15:14,908 --> 00:15:22,558
As soon as we give something of time or of wealth, we must be giving it away from ourselves.

159
00:15:22,578 --> 00:15:24,562
We must be giving something up.

160
00:15:24,581 --> 00:15:29,327
And in a sense, there are various degrees, as you know, of generosity.

161
00:15:29,347 --> 00:15:32,292
I mean, at Christmas, people swap gifts.

162
00:15:32,913 --> 00:15:35,836
So that's what kings do.

163
00:15:35,817 --> 00:15:37,379
When they meet, they swap gifts.

164
00:15:37,479 --> 00:15:38,801
It's just a friendship thing.

165
00:15:38,861 --> 00:15:41,706
It's a social nicety, you might say.

166
00:15:42,145 --> 00:15:43,427
But it has a purpose.

167
00:15:43,447 --> 00:15:53,644
But it's difficult to call it generosity, because if your lump of cheese didn't turn up, you'd be very upset, because you've gone and bought them another different type of cheese.

168
00:15:54,063 --> 00:15:58,171
So it's that sort of swapping of things, which is just a social nicety.

169
00:15:58,610 --> 00:16:03,158
But when it comes to real generosity, you know that you are...

170
00:16:03,138 --> 00:16:13,307
being generous when in a sense what you're giving actually is pushing the boundaries of what you want to give without of course harming yourself.

171
00:16:13,326 --> 00:16:17,197
I mean one doesn't want to give all one's wealth away and then end up on the streets.

172
00:16:18,173 --> 00:16:28,870
There's a lovely story of St. Francis, one of his monks or friars, brothers, taking this business of complete poverty as a standard, met somebody who needed clothes.

173
00:16:28,890 --> 00:16:30,553
So he gave him his robe and he came back naked.

174
00:16:31,033 --> 00:16:35,642
And so Francis had to make a rule that you can give everything away apart from your robe.

175
00:16:37,207 --> 00:16:42,038
There's a certain sort of, we have to use our common sense.

176
00:16:42,778 --> 00:16:53,822
But it's when you give of time, you see, give of time, that you know that when that boundary is being pushed, that actually you are truly beginning to renounce something.

177
00:16:55,645 --> 00:16:57,850
So I was just talking to my aunt there, and my aunt said,

178
00:16:58,471 --> 00:17:02,398
She belongs to that old school, she's middle eighties or something.

179
00:17:03,139 --> 00:17:17,403
And she was telling me that when Uncle John got sick, he was very old, she never went to bed for two years.

180
00:17:17,844 --> 00:17:19,467
She sat in a chair.

181
00:17:19,800 --> 00:17:25,066
One day he got up, he had a little stroke and at night he'd be disoriented.

182
00:17:25,287 --> 00:17:29,570
So one night she caught him trying to get out of the window and this really freaked her.

183
00:17:30,132 --> 00:17:37,740
So what she did was she put her armchair next to the window and sat there for two years, never went to bed.

184
00:17:38,359 --> 00:17:47,849
And she would amuse herself by listening to the radio and knitting and doing all sorts of stuff just for fear that he'd be sleepwalking and do something stupid.

185
00:17:48,826 --> 00:17:52,734
And it ruined her sleep pattern, which she's never particularly regained.

186
00:17:52,935 --> 00:17:56,785
And I'm just thinking, well, I wonder if I would do that then.

187
00:17:58,188 --> 00:18:00,574
I'd probably just chain them to the bed.

188
00:18:02,376 --> 00:18:05,082
put a manacle on their foot.

189
00:18:07,405 --> 00:18:11,574
So you've got these different ideas of generosity.

190
00:18:11,795 --> 00:18:15,141
And, you know, like that was her, she felt that was her duty.

191
00:18:15,300 --> 00:18:24,739
That was her, you know, she belongs to that age group, which talks about duty, not rights, you know, about responsibility rather than rights, my rights.

192
00:18:26,119 --> 00:18:35,359
So this generosity, of course, you can expand that into really all sorts of areas.

193
00:18:35,861 --> 00:18:45,039
So one of them, and it's funny, it's not actually in, I don't know why it's not in the Ten Perfections, it's, I think, presumed in the word love.

194
00:18:45,019 --> 00:18:58,259
Because when we chant the loving-kindness discourse, you can see that the Buddha is giving it a very wide meaning of just a loving relationship, which includes both compassion and joy.

195
00:18:59,642 --> 00:19:11,179
So when something comes up which demands us to help somebody who is in need, then the generosity manifests as compassion.

196
00:19:12,509 --> 00:19:16,256
So it's the same when somebody's rejoicing over something.

197
00:19:16,777 --> 00:19:23,469
So to rejoice with them, to be happy for them, is also an act of generosity.

198
00:19:24,130 --> 00:19:36,271
Even more so if you feel absolutely miserable and the world's gone completely wrong for you, but you're able to put that to the side and rejoice with the person who's being happy.

199
00:19:36,369 --> 00:19:38,291
That's also an act of generosity.

200
00:19:38,332 --> 00:19:44,038
So generosity is, in the widest sense of the term, is giving of oneself, you see.

201
00:19:44,357 --> 00:19:48,462
Emptying, sort of giving oneself, emptying oneself towards another.

202
00:19:49,443 --> 00:19:53,989
It's very beautiful how the Buddha talks about his relationship to the people he teaches.

203
00:19:55,349 --> 00:20:02,396
He says, whatever a teacher can do for his pupils, I have done for you, out of anukampan.

204
00:20:02,416 --> 00:20:04,960
Anukampan means to move towards somebody, you see.

205
00:20:05,394 --> 00:20:08,772
The word that most you know will be karuna, which is compassion.

206
00:20:09,277 --> 00:20:13,000
But the word he uses, anu kampan, is to move towards somebody.

207
00:20:13,602 --> 00:20:18,007
So when you see somebody who's in need, you move towards them.

208
00:20:18,548 --> 00:20:23,894
And it was one of the things on his big doubt, wasn't it?

209
00:20:23,913 --> 00:20:25,075
The great doubt, you see.

210
00:20:25,115 --> 00:20:32,523
So remember that in the great doubt when Mara arose and said, who the hell are you to try and become liberated from all suffering?

211
00:20:33,044 --> 00:20:37,009
You've been around everybody, you know everybody, and nobody's made it.

212
00:20:37,169 --> 00:20:38,810
And here, you're like...

213
00:20:38,790 --> 00:20:42,635
Where's this ego thing coming from, this pride?

214
00:20:43,537 --> 00:20:47,461
And it's when he touches the earth and the earth goddess arises.

215
00:20:48,162 --> 00:20:56,051
And she defends him by saying, because of his past lives, perfecting the virtue of generosity.

216
00:20:56,632 --> 00:20:57,713
So what does this mean?

217
00:20:57,794 --> 00:21:02,680
It means that he saw that what he was doing wasn't just for himself, it was for all beings.

218
00:21:03,240 --> 00:21:08,747
And that gave him the courage to withstand the doubt, the inner doubt as to...

219
00:21:08,727 --> 00:21:10,140
You know, what was he doing this for?

220
00:21:10,746 --> 00:21:11,936
This is ridiculous, you know?

221
00:21:14,498 --> 00:21:25,867
And that perfection of generosity was basically the, you know, if you want interpretation of that story is, that was the backbone of his effort.

222
00:21:26,269 --> 00:21:36,657
That he wasn't just a matter of me trying to liberate myself from suffering, but also remembering that, you know, probably remembered his own family and his son and all that sort of stuff.

223
00:21:36,678 --> 00:21:39,921
And then from then, all his friends and people like that.

224
00:21:39,941 --> 00:21:44,505
And it must have occurred to him that if he can crack this problem, then he's cracked it for everybody.

225
00:21:44,484 --> 00:21:52,156
So that gives your effort a meaningfulness which is just beyond yourself, doesn't it?

226
00:21:52,657 --> 00:22:01,531
I mean, if you're doing something for somebody else, for yourself, but also for somebody else, it gives it a much deeper meaning.

227
00:22:01,511 --> 00:22:06,038
And if we were to talk about happinesses, you can talk about three sort of levels.

228
00:22:06,758 --> 00:22:12,045
You know, one is the ordinary sensual happiness, which is fleeting and all that, but it's a happiness, you know, physical happiness.

229
00:22:12,505 --> 00:22:22,778
It can also be intellectual, artistic, even the joys of the practice, you know, when some peace arises very occasionally, then that's a...

230
00:22:22,758 --> 00:22:26,028
That is a bit of transient joy and to be enjoyed.

231
00:22:26,630 --> 00:22:30,162
And then there's that type of joy where you get lost in it.

232
00:22:30,301 --> 00:22:32,990
I think, what's his name?

233
00:22:33,151 --> 00:22:36,260
Aristotle called it eudominia.

234
00:22:37,134 --> 00:22:39,258
And it's when you get lost.

235
00:22:39,278 --> 00:22:41,981
It's when you lose the self in something, like a DVD, you see.

236
00:22:42,682 --> 00:22:44,705
And then you come out of it and suddenly you're there again.

237
00:22:45,067 --> 00:22:47,691
And during that moment, you've been perfectly happy.

238
00:22:48,451 --> 00:22:50,875
You've not been self-aware, but you have been perfectly happy.

239
00:22:50,895 --> 00:22:52,617
And then you come out of it and it's gone, you see.

240
00:22:53,619 --> 00:22:57,726
And it's catching that gone-ness that brings up.

241
00:22:57,705 --> 00:23:06,444
you know, this idea of not getting attached to something that you've become so involved in for happiness.

242
00:23:06,765 --> 00:23:09,471
But what you, you know, these,

243
00:23:10,513 --> 00:23:11,915
these surveys and whatnot.

244
00:23:11,935 --> 00:23:23,730
But what makes people really, really deeply happy, which has nothing to do really with transient emotions, because they arise and pass away, and always sends your pleasure, is meaningfulness.

245
00:23:24,551 --> 00:23:27,736
And when that meaningfulness goes, you have despair.

246
00:23:28,497 --> 00:23:36,166
So that's why I say people who lose meaninglessness, meaningfulness in their lives, are really on the point of despair.

247
00:23:36,146 --> 00:23:44,303
And there was these soldiers who commit suicide after war and whatnot, for whatever reason, psychologically.

248
00:23:44,324 --> 00:23:49,594
But seemingly, they all commit suicide because at some point, they despair.

249
00:23:49,894 --> 00:23:51,017
They despair, you see.

250
00:23:52,499 --> 00:24:01,983
And I had a woman phone me up just the other day, you see, in a dreadful state, just at the point of despair, you see, despair, just when you give up hope.

251
00:24:02,444 --> 00:24:07,217
And, of course, that's the sign, isn't it, on Dante's hell, you know, abandon all hope you all have.

252
00:24:07,686 --> 00:24:08,548
You enter here.

253
00:24:09,169 --> 00:24:16,978
So this idea of generosity has this very deep way of connecting us.

254
00:24:17,858 --> 00:24:23,064
And it's only then that our lives seem to take on a much deeper meaning.

255
00:24:24,726 --> 00:24:34,217
And in that meaning, that connectedness, that very deep sort of relationship, that is really love at its deepest level, isn't it?

256
00:24:34,400 --> 00:24:48,179
And when that's extended from human beings to animals and nature and the world and the cosmos and all that, then you suddenly find yourself in this lovely place of being interconnected.

257
00:24:48,499 --> 00:24:49,681
I mean, that's what it means, isn't it?

258
00:24:51,143 --> 00:24:53,346
And it comes about through generosity.

259
00:24:53,566 --> 00:24:55,028
It comes about through giving, compassion.

260
00:24:55,048 --> 00:24:58,653
It doesn't come about because you've thought about it and you've written an essay on interconnectedness.

261
00:24:59,314 --> 00:24:59,614
No.

262
00:25:00,758 --> 00:25:11,371
It actually comes about just because you've made that effort to give of yourself into that huge sort of matrix.

263
00:25:15,737 --> 00:25:17,920
And you can even see some of the other ones.

264
00:25:18,400 --> 00:25:21,044
So Selah, I mean, that's the dark side.

265
00:25:21,243 --> 00:25:25,128
You know, that's why we say you shouldn't kill and all that sort of stuff.

266
00:25:25,148 --> 00:25:27,811
And take what's not freely given and all those things.

267
00:25:28,146 --> 00:25:30,933
negative things of not to do that, not to do that.

268
00:25:30,953 --> 00:25:42,560
And I think you'll find that every time you are behaving unethically and even in the smallest, simplest, silly way that creates little qualms in the mind, there'll be something against one of those five.

269
00:25:43,772 --> 00:25:54,027
The whole rule of the Vinaya, apart from those that are specific to little rules and regulations, are all around these five basic rules.

270
00:25:54,087 --> 00:26:01,478
I mean, they're fundamental, aren't they, to our society, fundamental to our relationship.

271
00:26:01,458 --> 00:26:15,855
So, in correcting all the negative stuff that we do on those sides, anger, usual stuff, anger, you know, being callous, little sharp words that we might say to people.

272
00:26:16,875 --> 00:26:29,912
By correcting all that, you see, that is also to be seen as a generous act, you see, because you're giving up this inner desire to poke somebody in the eye, which can be very pleasurable.

273
00:26:32,203 --> 00:26:33,785
That's a sealer.

274
00:26:36,327 --> 00:26:37,087
Renunciation wisdom.

275
00:26:38,750 --> 00:26:39,529
Patience, you see.

276
00:26:40,030 --> 00:26:40,852
Patience is another one.

277
00:26:40,912 --> 00:26:45,756
Now the Buddha talks about a more sort of, what would you call it?

278
00:26:45,996 --> 00:26:48,178
I'm trying to think of another word apart from negative.

279
00:26:48,198 --> 00:26:49,019
It's not negative.

280
00:26:49,038 --> 00:26:56,125
It's just the other side of the more positive language.

281
00:26:57,385 --> 00:27:01,890
Where the Buddha talks about it as the greatest form of ascetic practice.

282
00:27:02,140 --> 00:27:04,703
So what does he mean by ascetic practice?

283
00:27:04,723 --> 00:27:07,689
He means, you know, bearing with suffering.

284
00:27:07,709 --> 00:27:19,269
So the self-mortificator, you know, starves themselves, sits next to fires for the heat, stands in the river Ganges for hours on end so the karma is washed away.

285
00:27:19,670 --> 00:27:21,532
And there's all sorts of...

286
00:27:21,512 --> 00:27:23,075
wonderful ascetic practices.

287
00:27:23,095 --> 00:27:29,163
There was even a Christian saint, somebody of, I can't remember his name now, but he sat on a pillar.

288
00:27:29,324 --> 00:27:30,405
He was up there all his life.

289
00:27:31,287 --> 00:27:32,088
And that was it.

290
00:27:32,128 --> 00:27:34,873
He lived on the top of this pillar.

291
00:27:34,893 --> 00:27:36,674
So these are things that probably came from the East.

292
00:27:37,175 --> 00:27:44,386
And you'll still see in India ascetics who've kept their arm up in the air and it's withered.

293
00:27:45,347 --> 00:27:46,710
You know, I mean, I've seen that myself.

294
00:27:48,461 --> 00:27:50,765
You know, because of some reasons.

295
00:27:50,884 --> 00:27:53,909
I mean, they have reasons for doing these things.

296
00:27:55,329 --> 00:28:00,596
So what he means by aesthetic practice is that, is to bear with, patient forbearance.

297
00:28:00,916 --> 00:28:02,638
And of course, it begins inward, doesn't it?

298
00:28:02,659 --> 00:28:10,268
Because all this stuff comes up and we've just got to patiently bear with these emotional states that come up within ourselves.

299
00:28:10,248 --> 00:28:13,971
But they're the same states that we see in other people.

300
00:28:13,991 --> 00:28:16,414
There's nothing that separates us apart from the stories.

301
00:28:16,575 --> 00:28:18,957
Everybody has fear.

302
00:28:19,417 --> 00:28:21,380
Everybody has depression, all that sort of stuff.

303
00:28:21,680 --> 00:28:22,922
But the stories are all different.

304
00:28:22,942 --> 00:28:24,202
They're all different dramas.

305
00:28:25,124 --> 00:28:31,090
But fundamentally, we've all got these same experiences of life.

306
00:28:31,951 --> 00:28:36,896
And bearing with somebody who's annoying us is an act of generosity, isn't it?

307
00:28:36,876 --> 00:28:40,522
You're sort of taking it on.

308
00:28:41,403 --> 00:28:45,750
Of course, you don't want to be abused by them, because that's another thing.

309
00:28:46,172 --> 00:28:52,903
When you talk about love and whatnot, people get confused that you have to give, give, give, even though you're being throttled.

310
00:28:54,365 --> 00:28:55,307
Give of your neck.

311
00:28:57,176 --> 00:29:11,170
I mean, there's a limit, you know, like as soon as the person's hurting you, then of course there's a different moral comes in where your love has lost its...

312
00:29:12,060 --> 00:29:15,948
has lost its connection with you personally.

313
00:29:16,670 --> 00:29:28,131
See, it's no good giving, giving, giving, and burning yourself out like a lot of people might do, especially, you know, caught up in things like ecology and all that, and they get very frustrated and angry and despairing.

314
00:29:28,751 --> 00:29:34,423
And it's all done with goodwill, with active, but they're burning themselves out, see?

315
00:29:35,972 --> 00:29:38,536
And he gives that lovely example, doesn't he?

316
00:29:39,676 --> 00:29:40,979
Somebody came along with a machete.

317
00:29:41,259 --> 00:29:44,682
He doesn't use that word, but he came along with a sword and chopped you from limb to limb.

318
00:29:44,803 --> 00:29:48,006
If ever you were even to be angry, you're no disciple of mine.

319
00:29:48,586 --> 00:29:52,571
I once said that in another talk.

320
00:29:52,592 --> 00:29:54,334
Somebody said, well, the Buddha had a great sense of humor.

321
00:29:56,596 --> 00:29:57,457
But I think he meant it.

322
00:29:58,097 --> 00:30:04,545
So this idea of bearing with people, patient forbearance, it's a perfection, you see.

323
00:30:06,500 --> 00:30:14,330
And it undermines all the other stuff as well, especially the whole thing about victimization, you know, being the victim and how people get caught up in that.

324
00:30:14,432 --> 00:30:15,333
You know, why me?

325
00:30:15,993 --> 00:30:18,156
It moves into a sort of self-pity, you see.

326
00:30:18,336 --> 00:30:20,240
And what happens is they're unable to forgive.

327
00:30:20,539 --> 00:30:23,664
So they're locked into a really dreadful.

328
00:30:23,644 --> 00:30:25,688
A dreadful state, dreadful state.

329
00:30:26,148 --> 00:30:29,493
They just can't get out of that because they have been hurt.

330
00:30:29,555 --> 00:30:31,417
Nobody's denying that and all that.

331
00:30:31,978 --> 00:30:33,461
But there's that self-pity.

332
00:30:33,701 --> 00:30:34,281
Why me?

333
00:30:34,301 --> 00:30:35,103
And the hatred.

334
00:30:35,644 --> 00:30:37,667
And so long as there's self-pity, you can't forgive.

335
00:30:38,848 --> 00:30:39,830
There's a block.

336
00:30:40,351 --> 00:30:52,203
And it's only when you begin to put yourself in the shoes of the other person who's done the harm and recognize that they also are going to have a lot of suffering because of the harm they've done.

337
00:30:52,263 --> 00:30:53,464
And how do we know that?

338
00:30:53,484 --> 00:31:04,096
By investigating the harm that we've done and recognizing that actually, internally, I'm not looking at the amount of suffering in me for the harm I've done to somebody else.

339
00:31:05,359 --> 00:31:12,990
And the greater the harm, the more difficult it is to forgive oneself, you see.

340
00:31:13,010 --> 00:31:16,977
So that whole victim thing can be a real lock.

341
00:31:17,538 --> 00:31:22,826
And patient forbearance is part of that process of forgiveness.

342
00:31:27,313 --> 00:31:30,017
There's, of course, energy, compassion.

343
00:31:31,499 --> 00:31:32,980
The Buddha is very tough on energy.

344
00:31:33,040 --> 00:31:48,903
I mean, the word comes up right there in the discourse on establishing right awareness, tapo, atapi, atapi, which comes from this word tapo, which comes up in the Mangala Sutta there.

345
00:31:49,182 --> 00:31:54,891
And it's the energy that you need to really, you know, complete a task.

346
00:31:55,984 --> 00:32:01,433
whatever it is, to complete the task, to finish it, you know, whatever you undertake.

347
00:32:02,935 --> 00:32:09,085
Often, you know, people, they come on a retreat, you see, they come on a retreat, it gets a bit tough.

348
00:32:09,306 --> 00:32:15,174
They made a resolution to stay the week, it gets a bit tough, and towards it they give up, you see.

349
00:32:15,756 --> 00:32:16,457
Now,

350
00:32:17,212 --> 00:32:23,461
what they're doing is that they're undermining their ability to perfect their commitments.

351
00:32:24,343 --> 00:32:28,087
So that any time it gets a bit difficult, there's always this little escape.

352
00:32:29,329 --> 00:32:30,090
That doesn't mean to say...

353
00:32:30,392 --> 00:32:38,041
I mean, on retreats, I'm sure you've heard me say that to commit yourself to the course, save an extraordinary circumstance or emergency.

354
00:32:38,603 --> 00:32:40,625
So it's not as though it's an absolute thing, you know.

355
00:32:41,326 --> 00:32:43,390
You know, I like it, you know, if...

356
00:32:44,196 --> 00:32:49,423
If the place caught fire, you're not supposed to sit there and, I will not leave this place.

357
00:32:49,923 --> 00:32:52,968
So there's also a sort of common sense.

358
00:32:53,429 --> 00:32:59,497
But whenever we say we're going to do something and we don't do it, we're actually harming ourselves.

359
00:32:59,777 --> 00:33:03,201
So, for instance, you might say to a friend, yeah, I'll come and decorate.

360
00:33:03,622 --> 00:33:07,166
And then your phone will tell you you're not feeling so well today.

361
00:33:08,327 --> 00:33:15,700
And it's like you're undermining this ability to make resolutions, to make determinations.

362
00:33:16,621 --> 00:33:27,057
And if you think again of the Buddha's own practice, the moment of great determination, to sit under that tree, either to crack this problem or to die.

363
00:33:27,278 --> 00:33:28,319
And that's where he got to.

364
00:33:29,280 --> 00:33:32,866
It was almost, you might say, a point of despair, you know.

365
00:33:33,116 --> 00:33:34,799
He had this little insight.

366
00:33:35,119 --> 00:33:39,227
He had this insight coming from childhood to actually investigate suffering.

367
00:33:39,247 --> 00:33:40,588
But he could see no other way.

368
00:33:40,788 --> 00:33:42,792
And if this didn't work, well, that was it.

369
00:33:43,252 --> 00:33:48,882
So he was prepared to sit there until he died with it.

370
00:33:49,462 --> 00:33:51,946
We call that the great determination.

371
00:33:52,709 --> 00:33:54,711
So that's this business of energy.

372
00:33:54,751 --> 00:33:58,156
The energy is needed, but resolution is the other perfection.

373
00:33:59,378 --> 00:34:00,441
But you need that energy.

374
00:34:03,626 --> 00:34:09,916
when you suffer from dullness and lethargy, you see, remember that is also an energy.

375
00:34:10,215 --> 00:34:11,557
So you don't look at it negatively.

376
00:34:11,597 --> 00:34:16,585
Don't think to yourself, well, you know, this is something dragging me down.

377
00:34:16,686 --> 00:34:19,028
It is dragging you down, but it's an actual force.

378
00:34:19,349 --> 00:34:21,152
It's a mental energy.

379
00:34:21,793 --> 00:34:22,673
It can also be physical.

380
00:34:23,514 --> 00:34:26,800
And if we just allow it to manifest,

381
00:34:26,780 --> 00:34:33,452
It also transforms, it also sublimates into its opposite, which is good energy.

382
00:34:33,592 --> 00:34:47,876
Sometimes it'll flip and become restlessness, but when it's actually moving towards its opposite, it's moving into this lovely flow of energy when our meditation is very easy for us.

383
00:34:50,539 --> 00:35:15,501
truthfulness here is something quite specific it's really keeping your promise rather than not telling great big budgies you know I mean that's part of it but it's actually when you say you do something that you actually do do it so you can see that that melds into the whole thing of resolution and stuff

384
00:35:17,083 --> 00:35:18,766
And the other one is wisdom, of course.

385
00:35:19,266 --> 00:35:20,708
I've not put them in the same order here.

386
00:35:20,989 --> 00:35:25,454
Wisdom is a mental, call it that, a mental virtue.

387
00:35:25,954 --> 00:35:27,536
So it's really understanding things.

388
00:35:27,737 --> 00:35:29,820
And really it all begins there, doesn't it?

389
00:35:30,101 --> 00:35:34,666
If we've misunderstood something, then things go awry.

390
00:35:35,407 --> 00:35:39,952
So we always have to come back to this, you know, the Buddha's...

391
00:35:39,932 --> 00:35:47,581
constant encouragement to reflect wisely, see, wise reflection, yoni so manasikara.

392
00:35:48,101 --> 00:35:57,451
So at the end of a sitting, that's why, you know, just to get in the habit of, even if you only pick up one thing from your sitting, to just think about it, let it come to mind.

393
00:35:57,811 --> 00:36:03,898
And at the end of a day, you see, just to look back for a moment, pick up one or two things, yeah.

394
00:36:03,878 --> 00:36:06,521
We have to be very careful not to always pick up the negative stuff.

395
00:36:06,541 --> 00:36:07,342
We're very good at that.

396
00:36:08,804 --> 00:36:10,547
We have to also pick up the positive stuff.

397
00:36:11,467 --> 00:36:13,110
Positive stuff that's happened to us today.

398
00:36:13,971 --> 00:36:14,652
What we've done today.

399
00:36:15,032 --> 00:36:18,577
And that's another thing about joy.

400
00:36:18,617 --> 00:36:21,380
You've got to actually excite joy within us.

401
00:36:21,420 --> 00:36:25,565
You've got to remember times when you were joyful.

402
00:36:26,844 --> 00:36:29,989
and understand how that joy came about.

403
00:36:30,510 --> 00:36:33,532
And this sort of builds up a well of joy, you see.

404
00:36:34,333 --> 00:36:38,478
We tend to be a bit negative usually, don't we?

405
00:36:38,539 --> 00:36:40,782
We tend to remember all the horrible things, because they hurt.

406
00:36:41,543 --> 00:36:45,467
The pleasurable things that don't hurt, they're all right.

407
00:36:45,929 --> 00:36:50,353
But by doing that, we get a sort of lopsided view of our lives sometimes.

408
00:36:50,474 --> 00:36:52,697
It's all miserable and horrible and all that.

409
00:36:52,717 --> 00:36:54,438
We forget that we've just had a good meal.

410
00:36:57,101 --> 00:37:02,070
So these are our paramita.

411
00:37:04,835 --> 00:37:06,257
The final one is equanimity.

412
00:37:06,739 --> 00:37:17,277
And it's arguable, definitely Nyanaponika Thera, who wrote that very good book, you know, The Heart of Buddhist Meditation.

413
00:37:17,356 --> 00:37:19,059
It still is really a classic book.

414
00:37:19,646 --> 00:37:30,099
But he also wrote other essays and in one he argues quite strongly that the perfection of equanimity is really the perfection because it balances everything.

415
00:37:30,820 --> 00:37:39,192
Although equanimity can have its own dark energy, its own dark side of indifference.

416
00:37:40,791 --> 00:37:46,659
it does have this ability to not to stop these things overriding, see?

417
00:37:47,159 --> 00:37:54,568
So that, you know, things like love doesn't become attachment, see?

418
00:37:54,628 --> 00:37:55,849
So seeing where the attachment is.

419
00:37:56,469 --> 00:37:57,050
How do you know?

420
00:37:57,351 --> 00:37:58,972
How do you know when you're attached, you see?

421
00:37:59,152 --> 00:38:00,193
Well, there's many ways, aren't there?

422
00:38:01,034 --> 00:38:04,378
Especially when you're getting irritated with somebody because they're not doing what you want them to do.

423
00:38:05,039 --> 00:38:07,001
That's an obvious case of...

424
00:38:07,807 --> 00:38:09,902
of attachment, see?

425
00:38:09,922 --> 00:38:12,840
Or when they disappoint you, when you're disappointed in somebody, see?

426
00:38:12,981 --> 00:38:14,612
Expectation, stuff like that.

427
00:38:16,027 --> 00:38:18,750
compassion slips into pity, doesn't it?

428
00:38:18,829 --> 00:38:19,670
Pity for somebody.

429
00:38:20,251 --> 00:38:27,059
And if you think about how you feel when somebody pities you, then you know how horrible it is for somebody who's being pitied by you.

430
00:38:28,701 --> 00:38:30,222
So it stops that, you see.

431
00:38:30,762 --> 00:38:40,313
And again, it's this business of being open to what the other person is asking for, not getting into that do-gooder thing.

432
00:38:42,199 --> 00:38:43,882
Joy slips into excitement.

433
00:38:44,242 --> 00:38:51,492
So you can, if you take any virtue, you'll see it has a little, it has a subtle energy, a subtle enemy, you see.

434
00:38:52,152 --> 00:38:54,936
So courage slips into foolhardiness.

435
00:38:57,659 --> 00:38:59,282
I can't think of any more.

436
00:38:59,663 --> 00:39:00,083
Mine's gone.

437
00:39:00,103 --> 00:39:07,954
But if you think of any virtue, it'll always have its little, slightly subtle negative side that it can slip into.

438
00:39:10,128 --> 00:39:12,032
I mean, we can talk about generosity.

439
00:39:12,273 --> 00:39:14,217
So it slips into over-generosity.

440
00:39:14,617 --> 00:39:20,731
It goes beyond what you're actually capable of doing, and you undermine yourself by doing that.

441
00:39:23,777 --> 00:39:30,110
So that's a quick run-through, you might say, of these paramita, these paramita.

442
00:39:34,900 --> 00:39:44,512
So it does say here, these qualities were developed and brought to maturity by the Bodhisattva in his past existences, in this way practicing them, illustrating the many birth stories of Jataka.

443
00:39:45,373 --> 00:39:48,717
However, it's only the verses that are regarded as canonical.

444
00:39:50,940 --> 00:39:53,824
That's of the stories around the Buddha.

445
00:39:54,284 --> 00:39:56,106
You know, where he's reborn as a hare and a...

446
00:39:59,010 --> 00:40:01,313
It's all Aesop's fables, really.

447
00:40:04,481 --> 00:40:17,202
So we can end this just by me reading this lovely little paragraph which expresses what the Bodhisattva or the person who wants to develop these ten perfections.

448
00:40:22,751 --> 00:40:27,840
As the great being, see Mahasattva, so that's synonymous really for the Bodhisattva,

449
00:40:30,300 --> 00:41:00,121
destined for Buddhahood are concerned with the welfare of living beings not tolerating the suffering of beings wishing long duration to the higher states of happiness of beings and being impartial and just to all beings therefore they give alms to all beings so that they may be happy without investigating whether or not they are worthy by avoiding to do them any harm

450
00:41:00,894 --> 00:41:27,391
observe morality and in order to bring morality to perfection they train themselves in renunciation in order to understand clearly what is beneficial and injurious to beings they purify their wisdom and for the sake of the welfare and happiness of others they constantly exert their energy though having become heroes through utmost energy

451
00:41:27,793 --> 00:41:32,597
they are nevertheless full of forbearance towards the manifold failings of beings.

452
00:41:34,519 --> 00:41:38,824
Once they have promised to give or to do something, they do not break their promise.

453
00:41:39,565 --> 00:41:40,344
That's the truthfulness.

454
00:41:41,626 --> 00:41:46,550
With unshakable resolution, they work for the will and welfare of beings.

455
00:41:47,592 --> 00:41:50,494
And with unshakable kindness, they are helpful to all.

456
00:41:51,414 --> 00:41:56,619
And by reason of their equanimity, they do not expect anything in return.

457
00:41:58,507 --> 00:42:02,612
It's nice, isn't it?

458
00:42:02,632 --> 00:42:11,442
I remember once this causing a bit of a discussion as to whether you should give without investigating whether they are worthy or not.

459
00:42:14,485 --> 00:42:19,231
This is commentary, remember, so we can feel free to question that one.

460
00:42:20,853 --> 00:42:23,956
So I hope my words have been of some assistance.

461
00:42:25,117 --> 00:42:39,447
And that you will soon perfect the perfections and enter into that wonderful place, Nibbana, sooner rather than later.

